create a landing page after log in. 
It should have an AAC tile, which is the current AAC mode 
add a "Movie Time" tile, which will enter the Movie Time mode

Movie time mode will allow the user to select a show from youtube to watch. if the user doesn't like any of the shows, he can dwell on a button to refresh the options. 
Once selected, the user will need to solve a simple question before being able to watch the show. 
every x minutes (as set in the Movie TIme settings that also has to be created) (use youtube iframe player api), the show will pause and will require using eye gaze to complete a short puzzle or game or quiz before continuing. the types of games/puzzles/question can be set in settings and will be aided with AI. 
if the user looks away from the screen for more than y ms (also set in settings), the video will pause. 
In settings create a full fledge filter with AI to configure types of videos that can be made available including a list of whitelist keywords, blacklist keywords, length criteria, topics, safesearch etc. allow options for using gamer loophole, eg high quality fan creations 


in movie time settings, break it into 3 tabs: 
1) Playback 
2) Content 
a. (add a "interest" list similar to the whitelist where the user can add topics, however, this is an OR operator search. ie the search must include at least one topic from this list. 
b. add a youtube URL list where the user can also add and remove. videos from this list can always be made available for user to select. Add a button to allow ONLY videos from this list. 
3) puzzle  

1. build both implicit and explicit but have options to toggle them on or off. add settings to eye tracker settings. for the explicit version, feel free to change the positions and number of dots required for a balance of speed and accuracy 
2. correction should persist across sessions. it should also be visible to the user in eye tracker settings graphically. 
3. show the quality of eye tracking discreetly near the title bar or at the bottom somewhere in all parts of the screen where eyetracking is used. 